To decrypt a Caesar cipher, we need to determine the shift value used for encryption. The Caesar cipher is a type of substitution cipher where each letter in the plaintext is shifted a certain number of places down the alphabet.

The text provided is: "ESFQ KESDD VGFSLAGFK LG SJW HSJLAUMDSJDQ AEHGJLSFL LG ESAFLSAFAFY LSP WPWEHL KLSLMK OALZ LZW AJK."

To decrypt this, we will try all possible shifts (from 1 to 25) and check which one results in a meaningful English sentence. We will write a Python script to automate this process.

